article.headline: Swoopes scores 14 in second half
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Despite tremendous adversity, the Houston Comets
topped the Seattle Storm 63-57 behind the 18 points of Sheryl
Swoopes Tuesday night.

With top scorer Tina Thompson on the injured list and center
Michelle Snow in foul trouble the whole night, the Comets managed
to do enough when it mattered to snap the Storm's franchise-best
six-game winning streak.

"Despite the adversity, we found a way to win," Houston head
coach Van Chancellor said. "I can't say enough this basketball
team tonight. They played the team that's playing the best
basketball in the WNBA on their home court and won the game. That's
hard to do."

Swoopes scored 14 of her points in the second half, including
six in the final three minutes to keep the Comets (7-6) ahead for
good.

"This was a huge win for us after losing two in a row,"
Swoopes said. "We beat a very good team that was playing extremely
well. That says a lot about the talent we have on this team and the
confidence we have in ourselves and each other."

The Comets, who also got 15 points from Sheila Lambert, lost to
the Storm in Houston last week.

"We felt like we let that one slip away," Swoopes said. "We
obviously wanted to redeem ourselves."

Seattle (8-3) still has the league's best record, but didn't
play well. The Storm shot only 36 percent, and were outscored 40-26
in the paint.

Lauren Jackson led Seattle with 16 points.

"It's bad that we lost, but it's not the end of the world
because it's only one game," Jackson said.

Storm head coach Anne Donovan had a different take on the
importance of the loss.

"We are very cognizant that we missed the playoffs by half a
game last year," Donovan said. "Every game matters, and we didn't
play like we needed to."

Houston led 47-42 with 9:37 to play, but Seattle came back to
tie the score at 53 on a jumper by Kamila Vodichkova with 4:50
remaining.

Swoopes took over during the final minutes and put the Storm
away.

Lambert hit five of her first six shots and had 10 points in the
first half for Houston.

Betty Lennox added 14 points, Sheri Sam 11 and Vodichkova 10
points and 12 rebounds for Seattle.

Following back-to-back 3-pointers by Lennox that put the Storm
ahead 17-15 eight minutes into the first half, the Comets had an
8-2 run over the next 2:45. A pair of driving layups by Lambert put
Houston up 23-19.

Despite shooting 50 percent in the first half, the Comets
trailed 30-29 at the break.
